    pearls: ["AKI prevention is better than treatment: maintain perfusion, avoid nephrotoxins, hydrate before contrast", "FENa <1% = prerenal (kidneys retaining sodium appropriately); FENa >2% = intrinsic (tubular damage, cannot concentrate)", "Diuretics do NOT improve AKI outcomes but manage complications (fluid overload)", "Hyperkalemia management order: (1) Stabilize membrane (calcium), (2) Shift K intracellularly (insulin/glucose, albuterol, bicarb), (3) Remove K from body (diuretics, Kayexalate, dialysis)", "Serum creatinine is a LAGGING indicator: AKI has already occurred by the time creatinine rises"],
